notes: Native to Europe, aka White Poplar
Occurs where P. alba females are present.
Not common in the wild since most P. albas are females and P. grandidentata seed has more exacting requirements.
Not as common in the wild as AG
A valuable cross - used by itself or with CAGs
A double hybrid cross pioneered by the Canadians and known for diversity with some good rooting individuals despite poor rooting parents.
species_hybrid: (P. alba x P. grandidentata) x P. canescens

notes: Describes an open pollinated (Wind) CAG cross.  They may have potential for interesting recombinations.
species_hybrid: (P. canescens x (P. alba x P. grandidentata)) x OP

notes: Alternate name for CAG crosses for brevity.  A double hybrid cross pioneered by the Canadians and known for diversity with some good rooting individuals despite poor rooting parents.
species_hybrid: (P. alba x P. grandidentata) x P. canescens

notes: Alternate name for AG/GA crosses (P. xrouleauiana) for brevity.
species_hybrid: P. alba x P. grandidentata (and reciprocal)

notes: Alternate name for the TG/GT smithii (P. xsmithii Boivin) crosses for brevity
species_hybrid: P. tremuloides x P. grandidentata (and reciprocal)

notes: W stands for Wind pollinated. Therefore the exact male parent is unknown.
